    <h1> Common Cyber Threats </h1>
<p> As technology advances, so do the methods used by cybercriminals. Understanding common cyber threats is the first step in defending yourself against them. 
    Attackers use various techniques to steal data, hijack systems, or trick individuals into handing over sensitive information. 
    By familiarizing yourself with these dangers, you can spot them before they cause harm. </p>

    <img src="Images/4615955.png" width ="200"/>

<h2> Phishing Attacks </h2>
<p> Phishing is one of the most common and dangerous threats on the internet. In a phishing attack, a cybercriminal impersonates a legitimate organization—like a bank, a popular website, or even the government—often through email or text messages. 
    Their goal is to trick you into clicking a malicious link and entering your passwords, credit card numbers, or other personal data.</p>

<h2> Malware and Ransomware </h2>
<p> Malware (malicious software) is any software designed to harm or exploit computers and networks. This includes viruses, worms, and spyware. 
    A specific and highly damaging type of malware is <strong>Ransomware</strong>. It locks or encrypts your files and systems, and the attackers demand a ransom payment (usually in cryptocurrency) in exchange for the decryption key.</p>

    <img src="Images/556261.png" width="250" />

<h3> Other Notable Threats </h3>
<ol> 
    <li> Social Engineering – Manipulating people into breaking normal security procedures to gain confidential info. </li>
    <li> DDoS Attacks – Overwhelming a website or network with fake traffic so that legitimate users cannot access it. </li> 
    <li> Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) – Intercepting communication between two parties to steal data being transferred, often happening on unsecured public Wi-Fi. </li>
</ol>

<p> To stay updated on the latest cyber threats and how to avoid them, you can check out the official threat alerts from <a href="https://www.cisa.gov/known-exploited-vulnerabilities-catalog" target="_blank"> CISA (Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency) </a>.</p>

